items.text: I set ambitious goals for myself and work tirelessly until I reach them.
items.rationale: Directly reflects the drive to set and accomplish goals, a core facet of Achievement Orientation.

items.text: My self-worth is closely tied to how successful I am in the eyes of others.
items.rationale: Links identity and value to external markers of success, central to Enneagram Type 3 achievement drive.

items.text: I constantly compare my accomplishments to those of my peers.
items.rationale: Competitive benchmarking of success is a hallmark of achievement-oriented individuals.

items.text: When I fail at something, I feel like I've lost a part of my identity.
items.rationale: Fusing identity with performance outcomes is a defining feature of Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I naturally adapt my presentation to impress whatever audience I'm with.
items.rationale: Image management in service of appearing successful is core to achievement-driven personalities.

items.text: I have a hard time relaxing because there's always something more I could be doing.
items.rationale: Restless productivity and inability to disengage from work reflect strong achievement drive.

items.text: People describe me as someone who is always striving to be the best.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of relentless striving maps clearly to Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I feel most alive when I'm working toward a challenging objective.
items.rationale: Experiencing vitality through goal pursuit is a core motivational feature of this factor.

items.text: I tend to measure my day by how productive I was rather than how I felt.
items.rationale: Prioritizing output over emotional experience reflects achievement-centered self-evaluation.

items.text: I often take on leadership roles because I want to be seen as competent and effective.
items.rationale: Seeking leadership for image and competence validation is characteristic of achievement orientation.

items.text: Winning isn't everything to me—it's the only thing that matters.
items.rationale: Extreme competitive focus on winning is a strong indicator of Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I carefully curate how I appear on social media to project an image of success.
items.rationale: Deliberate image crafting for success perception is a modern behavioral marker of this factor.

items.text: I sometimes cut corners to get results faster, as long as it still looks impressive.
items.rationale: Prioritizing appearance of results over process could also reflect low conscientiousness, but the emphasis on impression maps to Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I push myself hard even when no one is watching, because I hold myself to high standards.
items.rationale: Internal standards could reflect conscientiousness broadly, but the self-pushing quality aligns with Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I get jealous when someone else receives recognition that I feel I deserved.
items.rationale: Jealousy over recognition could map to Envy, but the focus on deserved achievement credit anchors it in Achievement Orientation.

items.text: I can easily shift my approach when circumstances change unexpectedly.
items.rationale: Behavioral flexibility in response to changing conditions is the core definition of Adaptability.

items.text: I tend to go along with what the group wants rather than insist on my own preferences.
items.rationale: Merging with group preferences and suppressing personal agenda is characteristic of adaptive, Nine-like tendencies.

items.text: People say I'm a chameleon—I seem to become a different person depending on who I'm with.
items.rationale: Social shape-shifting is a hallmark behavioral description of high Adaptability.

items.text: I find it easy to see multiple perspectives in any disagreement.
items.rationale: Perspective-taking flexibility is a cognitive facet of Adaptability.

items.text: I rarely get upset when plans change at the last minute.
items.rationale: Emotional equanimity in the face of disrupted plans directly reflects adaptive capacity.

items.text: I'd rather keep the peace than fight for what I want.
items.rationale: Conflict avoidance through accommodation is a key behavioral pattern of high Adaptability.

items.text: I sometimes lose track of what I actually want because I'm so focused on fitting in.
items.rationale: Loss of personal identity through excessive accommodation is a shadow side of Adaptability.

items.text: I'm comfortable in ambiguous situations where the rules aren't clearly defined.
items.rationale: Tolerance for ambiguity is a cognitive hallmark of adaptable individuals.

items.text: When someone asks me where I want to eat, I genuinely don't have a strong preference.
items.rationale: Absence of strong personal preferences in everyday decisions reflects the merging quality of Adaptability.

items.text: I can work effectively with almost anyone, regardless of personality differences.
items.rationale: Interpersonal flexibility across diverse personalities is a practical expression of Adaptability.

items.text: I've been told I'm too agreeable and need to stand up for myself more.
items.rationale: Third-person feedback about excessive agreeableness maps to the over-accommodating side of Adaptability.

items.text: I thrive in environments that are constantly changing and evolving.
items.rationale: Preference for dynamic environments reflects comfort with change, a core Adaptability trait.

items.text: I often suppress my own opinions to avoid creating tension in a group.
items.rationale: Opinion suppression could reflect low Assertiveness, but the motivation of group harmony anchors it in Adaptability.

items.text: I'm good at reading the room and adjusting my behavior accordingly.
items.rationale: Social perceptiveness could also relate to Emotional Sensitivity, but the behavioral adjustment component maps to Adaptability.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I don't have a strong sense of who I really am.
items.rationale: Identity diffusion could map to Emotional Sensitivity or even Envy (longing for a clear identity), but in context of over-merging it reflects Adaptability.

items.text: I feel a simmering resentment that I can't always explain or justify.
items.rationale: Chronic, diffuse resentment is a core manifestation of the Anger factor, especially in body-center types.

items.text: When I see injustice, I feel a powerful urge to correct it immediately.
items.rationale: Righteous indignation and the impulse to correct wrongs is a hallmark of Enneagram Type 1 anger.

items.text: I have strong opinions about right and wrong, and I'm not afraid to voice them.
items.rationale: Moral conviction expressed forcefully reflects the principled anger of this factor.

items.text: I often feel frustrated with people who don't follow the rules or do things properly.
items.rationale: Frustration with others' lack of standards is a classic expression of internalized anger.

items.text: My inner critic is relentless—I'm constantly judging myself and others.
items.rationale: A harsh inner critic that extends to others is a defining cognitive pattern of the Anger factor.

items.text: I try to control my anger, but it leaks out as irritability and impatience.
items.rationale: Suppressed anger manifesting as irritability is a well-documented pattern in anger-dominant types.

items.text: People have told me I can be intimidating even when I don't mean to be.
items.rationale: Unintentional intimidation through intensity reflects the somatic presence of the Anger factor.

items.text: I hold grudges longer than I'd like to admit.
items.rationale: Persistent grudge-holding is a behavioral marker of unresolved anger.

items.text: I feel physically tense much of the time, especially in my jaw and shoulders.
items.rationale: Somatic tension in anger-associated muscle groups is a body-based indicator of chronic anger.

items.text: I believe the world would be a better place if people just did things the right way.
items.rationale: Perfectionist worldview driven by moral standards is a cognitive hallmark of the Anger factor.

items.text: When I'm angry, I tend to become cold and controlled rather than explosive.
items.rationale: Controlled, repressed anger expression is characteristic of internalized anger patterns.

items.text: I frequently replay situations in my mind where I felt wronged or disrespected.
items.rationale: Rumination on perceived wrongs is a cognitive-emotional pattern strongly associated with Anger.

items.text: I sometimes snap at people and then feel guilty about it afterward.
items.rationale: The guilt component could relate to Emotional Sensitivity, but the snapping behavior is primarily an Anger indicator.

items.text: I get deeply frustrated when things aren't organized or efficient.
items.rationale: Frustration with disorganization could reflect Achievement Orientation, but the emotional intensity maps to Anger.

items.text: I channel my intense energy into physical exercise or demanding projects.
items.rationale: Channeling intensity into action could map to Assertiveness (Type 8 energy), but the underlying tension suggests Anger.

items.text: I constantly worry about what could go wrong in any situation.
items.rationale: Chronic worry and catastrophic thinking are the defining features of the Anxiety factor.

items.text: I tend to overthink decisions because I'm afraid of making the wrong choice.
items.rationale: Decision paralysis driven by fear of error is a classic anxiety pattern.

items.text: I look to authority figures or trusted friends for reassurance before taking action.
items.rationale: Reassurance-seeking from authority is a hallmark of Type 6 anxiety patterns.

items.text: My mind races with worst-case scenarios, especially late at night.
items.rationale: Intrusive worst-case thinking is a core cognitive manifestation of Anxiety.

items.text: I have trouble trusting people until they've proven themselves over a long period.
items.rationale: Difficulty with trust and need for extended proof reflects the vigilance and suspicion of the Anxiety factor.

items.text: I often second-guess myself even after I've already made a decision.
items.rationale: Post-decision doubt and rumination are characteristic cognitive patterns of high Anxiety.

items.text: I feel safest when I have a detailed plan and know exactly what to expect.
items.rationale: Need for predictability and detailed planning as a safety strategy is core to Anxiety.

items.text: I'm hypervigilant about potential threats or dangers in my environment.
items.rationale: Environmental hypervigilance is a behavioral hallmark of the Anxiety factor.

items.text: I question people's motives, even when they seem to be acting kindly toward me.
items.rationale: Suspicion of others' motives reflects the trust difficulties central to Anxiety.

items.text: I prepare extensively for meetings or events because I'm terrified of being caught off guard.
items.rationale: Over-preparation driven by fear of surprise is a behavioral coping strategy for Anxiety.

items.text: I often feel a knot in my stomach when facing uncertain situations.
items.rationale: Somatic anxiety symptoms in response to uncertainty are a direct physiological marker of this factor.

items.text: I sometimes test people's loyalty to see if they'll really be there for me.
items.rationale: Loyalty testing is a relational behavior driven by the trust concerns central to Anxiety.

items.text: I find it hard to commit to things because I'm afraid of being trapped in a bad situation.
items.rationale: Commitment avoidance could relate to Adaptability, but the fear-based motivation maps it to Anxiety.

items.text: I tend to play devil's advocate in conversations, questioning assumptions others take for granted.
items.rationale: Contrarian questioning could reflect intellectual engagement, but when driven by doubt it maps to Anxiety.

items.text: I oscillate between trusting authority completely and rebelling against it.
items.rationale: This ambivalence toward authority could map to Assertiveness (counter-phobic rebellion), but the oscillation pattern is characteristic of Anxiety.

items.text: I have no problem telling people exactly what I think, even if it's uncomfortable.
items.rationale: Direct, unfiltered communication regardless of social comfort is a core expression of Assertiveness.

items.text: I naturally take charge in situations where no one else is stepping up.
items.rationale: Spontaneous assumption of leadership in power vacuums is a behavioral hallmark of Assertiveness.

items.text: I feel most comfortable when I'm in control of what's happening around me.
items.rationale: Need for environmental control is a defining motivational feature of the Assertiveness factor.

items.text: I'd rather confront a problem head-on than let it fester.
items.rationale: Direct confrontation preference over avoidance is a core behavioral pattern of Assertiveness.

items.text: People either love me or hate me—there's rarely an in-between.
items.rationale: Polarizing interpersonal impact reflects the intensity and directness of high Assertiveness.

items.text: I protect the people I care about fiercely, and I won't tolerate anyone mistreating them.
items.rationale: Fierce protectiveness of one's inner circle is a relational expression of Type 8 Assertiveness.

items.text: I can sense weakness in others almost immediately.
items.rationale: Acute perception of vulnerability in others is a characteristic interpersonal awareness of assertive types.

items.text: I respect people who stand their ground with me, even if I disagree with them.
items.rationale: Valuing strength and directness in others reflects the assertive person's interpersonal value system.

items.text: I hate feeling vulnerable or dependent on anyone else.
items.rationale: Aversion to vulnerability and dependence is a core defensive motivation of the Assertiveness factor.

items.text: When someone tries to manipulate me, I become intensely confrontational.
items.rationale: Aggressive response to perceived manipulation reflects the justice-oriented intensity of Assertiveness.

items.text: I have a big presence—when I walk into a room, people notice.
items.rationale: Commanding physical and energetic presence is a somatic marker of high Assertiveness.

items.text: I believe that showing weakness invites others to take advantage of you.
items.rationale: This belief about vulnerability and exploitation is a core cognitive schema of the Assertiveness factor.

items.text: I sometimes come across as domineering even when I'm just trying to help.
items.rationale: Unintentional dominance could also relate to Anger, but the helping intention with forceful delivery maps to Assertiveness.

items.text: I make decisions quickly and trust my gut instinct.
items.rationale: Rapid, instinct-based decision-making could reflect low Anxiety, but the confidence and action-orientation map to Assertiveness.

items.text: I get angry when I see powerful people exploiting those who can't defend themselves.
items.rationale: Anger at injustice could map to the Anger factor, but the focus on power dynamics and protection of the vulnerable is characteristic of Assertiveness.

items.text: I guard my time, energy, and resources very carefully.
items.rationale: Careful guarding of personal resources is the defining behavioral pattern of Avarice.

items.text: I prefer to observe life from a distance rather than fully participate in it.
items.rationale: Detached observation over participation reflects the withdrawal and hoarding of engagement characteristic of Avarice.

items.text: I need a lot of alone time to recharge, and I resent when people intrude on it.
items.rationale: Fierce protection of solitude and resentment of intrusion reflects the resource-guarding of Avarice.

items.text: I tend to minimize my needs and live with less than most people would find comfortable.
items.rationale: Minimizing needs to reduce dependence on external resources is a core strategy of Avarice.

items.text: I feel drained by social interactions and need to retreat to recover.
items.rationale: Social depletion and need for retreat reflects the energy conservation central to Avarice.

items.text: I'd rather figure things out on my own than ask someone for help.
items.rationale: Self-reliance and reluctance to seek help reflects the independence and resource-hoarding of Avarice.

items.text: I accumulate knowledge and information but rarely share it unless specifically asked.
items.rationale: Hoarding knowledge and sharing reluctantly is a cognitive-behavioral expression of Avarice.

items.text: I feel uncomfortable when people expect too much emotional engagement from me.
items.rationale: Discomfort with emotional demands reflects the withholding of inner resources characteristic of Avarice.

items.text: I often feel like the world demands more from me than I have to give.
items.rationale: Perception of excessive external demands on limited internal resources is a core experience of Avarice.

items.text: I'm very selective about who I let into my inner world.
items.rationale: Gatekeeping access to one's inner life reflects the protective withholding of Avarice.

items.text: I find it difficult to be generous with my time because it feels like giving away a piece of myself.
items.rationale: Experiencing generosity as self-depletion is a defining emotional experience of Avarice.

items.text: I compartmentalize my life—different people know different parts of me, but no one knows all of me.
items.rationale: Compartmentalization as a strategy to protect inner resources is characteristic of Avarice.

items.text: I sometimes hoard things I might need later, even if I don't need them now.
items.rationale: Physical hoarding could reflect general anxiety about scarcity, but the retention pattern maps to Avarice.

items.text: I prefer deep one-on-one conversations over large group gatherings.
items.rationale: Preference for intimate interaction could reflect introversion broadly, but the energy management aspect maps to Avarice.

items.text: I withdraw from people when I'm stressed rather than reaching out for support.
items.rationale: Stress withdrawal could map to Anxiety (avoidant coping), but the self-containment motivation is more characteristic of Avarice.

items.text: I spend a lot of time thinking about how I come across to other people.
items.rationale: Preoccupation with self-image and others' perceptions is a core feature of the Ego factor.

items.text: I need to feel special and unique—being ordinary is my worst fear.
items.rationale: Fear of ordinariness and need for uniqueness is a defining motivation of the Ego factor.

items.text: I have a strong sense of personal pride and find it hard to admit when I'm wrong.
items.rationale: Pride and difficulty acknowledging error reflect the self-image protection central to Ego.

items.text: I often feel that I'm more capable or insightful than the people around me.
items.rationale: Sense of superiority over others is a cognitive hallmark of inflated Ego.

items.text: I shape-shift to be whatever people need me to be, because I want to be indispensable.
items.rationale: Becoming indispensable through image management reflects the interpersonal strategy of the Ego factor (Type 2/3 dynamics).

items.text: I feel deeply wounded when someone doesn't recognize my contributions or value.
items.rationale: Narcissistic injury from lack of recognition is a core emotional vulnerability of the Ego factor.

items.text: I invest significant energy in maintaining a polished and attractive self-image.
items.rationale: Active investment in self-image maintenance is a behavioral hallmark of the Ego factor.

items.text: I sometimes exaggerate my accomplishments to make a stronger impression.
items.rationale: Self-aggrandizement through exaggeration is a direct behavioral expression of Ego inflation.

items.text: I find it very difficult to ask for help because it makes me feel weak or incompetent.
items.rationale: Equating help-seeking with weakness reflects the self-sufficiency demands of the Ego factor.

items.text: I'm highly aware of social hierarchies and where I stand in them.
items.rationale: Acute awareness of social status and positioning is a cognitive feature of the Ego factor.

items.text: I take criticism very personally, even when it's meant to be constructive.
items.rationale: Hypersensitivity to criticism reflects the fragility underlying Ego investment in self-image.

items.text: I believe I have a special purpose or destiny that sets me apart from others.
items.rationale: Belief in personal exceptionalism is a grandiose cognitive pattern of the Ego factor.

items.text: I sometimes feel like I'm performing a role rather than being my authentic self.
items.rationale: Awareness of self-performance could relate to Adaptability, but the identity-image disconnect is more characteristic of Ego.

items.text: I work hard to make sure people like and admire me.
items.rationale: Seeking admiration could overlap with Achievement Orientation, but the interpersonal approval focus maps to Ego.

items.text: I feel a deep need to be seen as helpful and generous by the people in my life.
items.rationale: Need to be seen as helpful could map to Emotional Sensitivity (Type 2 helping), but the emphasis on being seen reflects Ego.

items.text: I feel other people's pain as if it were my own.
items.rationale: Empathic absorption of others' pain is a defining feature of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I instinctively know what someone needs emotionally, often before they do.
items.rationale: Intuitive emotional attunement to others is a core interpersonal skill of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I have a hard time saying no to people because I don't want to hurt their feelings.
items.rationale: Difficulty with refusal driven by concern for others' feelings is characteristic of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I tend to prioritize other people's needs over my own, sometimes to my detriment.
items.rationale: Self-sacrificing prioritization of others' needs is a hallmark behavioral pattern of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I'm deeply moved by music, art, and stories of human struggle.
items.rationale: Deep aesthetic and empathic responsiveness reflects the emotional depth of this factor.

items.text: I can walk into a room and immediately sense the emotional atmosphere.
items.rationale: Acute sensitivity to ambient emotional energy is a perceptual hallmark of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I often cry during movies or when hearing about someone else's hardship.
items.rationale: Easy emotional activation through empathic engagement is a direct behavioral marker of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I feel responsible for making sure everyone around me is emotionally okay.
items.rationale: Assuming emotional caretaking responsibility for others is a core relational pattern of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I absorb the moods of the people around me like a sponge.
items.rationale: Emotional contagion and mood absorption are defining experiences of high Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I'm the person everyone comes to when they need someone to listen.
items.rationale: Being sought out as an emotional confidant reflects the perceived warmth and attunement of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I sometimes feel emotionally exhausted from carrying other people's burdens.
items.rationale: Compassion fatigue from over-engagement with others' emotions is a consequence of high Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I notice subtle shifts in people's tone of voice or facial expressions that others miss.
items.rationale: Heightened perceptual sensitivity to nonverbal emotional cues is a core ability of Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I sometimes resent that I give so much to others and don't receive the same in return.
items.rationale: Resentment about unreciprocated giving could relate to Anger, but the relational giving context maps to Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I find it hard to distinguish between my own emotions and those of the people around me.
items.rationale: Emotional boundary confusion could relate to Adaptability (merging), but the emotional nature of the experience maps to Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I secretly keep track of what I've done for others and feel hurt when it's not acknowledged.
items.rationale: Tracking contributions and seeking acknowledgment could map to Ego (need for recognition), but the relational hurt anchors it in Emotional Sensitivity.

items.text: I approach life with a sense of excitement and possibility—there's always something new to explore.
items.rationale: Excitement about possibilities and novelty-seeking is the core motivational pattern of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I have so many interests and projects going on that I struggle to finish any of them.
items.rationale: Overcommitment to multiple interests with difficulty completing them is a hallmark of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I hate feeling limited or constrained—I need freedom to pursue whatever catches my attention.
items.rationale: Aversion to limitation and need for freedom is a defining motivation of the Enthusiasm factor.

items.text: I'm usually the most upbeat and energetic person in any group.
items.rationale: Consistently high energy and positivity in social settings is a behavioral marker of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I reframe negative experiences quickly—I always find the silver lining.
items.rationale: Rapid positive reframing is a cognitive defense mechanism characteristic of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I get bored easily and constantly need new stimulation to stay engaged.
items.rationale: Low boredom threshold and need for stimulation are core features of the Enthusiasm factor.

items.text: I'd rather have a wide range of experiences than go deep into just one thing.
items.rationale: Breadth over depth preference in experience-seeking is a defining pattern of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I use humor and storytelling to keep conversations lively and entertaining.
items.rationale: Using humor and narrative to energize social interactions is a behavioral expression of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I have a hard time sitting with painful emotions—I'd rather distract myself with something fun.
items.rationale: Avoidance of painful emotions through pleasurable distraction is a core defensive strategy of Enthusiasm.

items.text: My calendar is always packed because I can't resist saying yes to exciting opportunities.
items.rationale: Overbooked schedules from inability to decline opportunities reflects the acquisitive nature of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I'm a natural brainstormer—I generate ideas faster than I can execute them.
items.rationale: Prolific idea generation outpacing execution capacity is a cognitive hallmark of Enthusiasm.

items.text: People describe me as infectious—my energy lifts the mood of everyone around me.
items.rationale: Contagious positive energy that elevates group mood is a social impact marker of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I sometimes use busyness and activity to avoid dealing with deeper emotional issues.
items.rationale: Using activity as emotional avoidance could relate to Achievement Orientation, but the avoidance of pain through stimulation maps to Enthusiasm.

items.text: I love planning trips and adventures, sometimes more than actually going on them.
items.rationale: Anticipatory pleasure exceeding actual experience could reflect general optimism, but the future-oriented excitement maps to Enthusiasm.

items.text: I feel restless and trapped when I'm stuck in a routine with no variety.
items.rationale: Restlessness in routine could map to Anxiety (feeling trapped), but the desire for variety and stimulation is more characteristic of Enthusiasm.

items.text: I often feel like something essential is missing from my life, but I can't quite name what it is.
items.rationale: A pervasive sense of something missing is the core emotional experience of the Envy factor.

items.text: When I see other people's happiness, I feel a painful awareness of what I lack.
items.rationale: Painful comparison with others' happiness is a defining emotional pattern of Envy.

items.text: I'm drawn to melancholy and find beauty in sadness that others don't understand.
items.rationale: Aesthetic attraction to melancholy and romanticization of sadness is characteristic of the Envy factor.

items.text: I feel like other people have an ease in life that I've never been able to access.
items.rationale: Perception that others possess an effortless quality one lacks is a core cognitive distortion of Envy.

items.text: I experience emotions more intensely than most people, and I wouldn't have it any other way.
items.rationale: Emotional intensity coupled with pride in that intensity is characteristic of the Envy factor's identity.

items.text: I tend to dwell on past losses and what might have been.
items.rationale: Rumination on loss and counterfactual thinking is a cognitive pattern central to Envy.

items.text: I feel fundamentally different from other people, as if I don't quite belong anywhere.
items.rationale: Sense of fundamental otherness and not belonging is a core identity experience of the Envy factor.

items.text: I push people away and then feel abandoned when they leave.
items.rationale: The push-pull relational pattern creating self-fulfilling abandonment is characteristic of Envy.

items.text: I'm attracted to what's distant or unavailable and lose interest in what's right in front of me.
items.rationale: Longing for the unavailable while devaluing the present is a defining pattern of the Envy factor.

items.text: I use my emotional depth and creativity to express what others can't put into words.
items.rationale: Channeling emotional depth into unique creative expression is a sublimation pattern of the Envy factor.

items.text: I feel a deep longing for a connection or experience that seems just out of reach.
items.rationale: Persistent longing for something unattainable is the quintessential emotional state of Envy.

items.text: I sometimes withdraw from social situations because I feel too emotionally raw to participate.
items.rationale: Social withdrawal due to emotional overwhelm reflects the intensity and vulnerability of the Envy factor.

items.text: I have a rich inner fantasy life that sometimes feels more real than my actual life.
items.rationale: Rich inner fantasy could relate to Avarice (inner world preference), but the emotional longing quality maps to Envy.

items.text: I feel a stab of pain when a close friend achieves something I've been wanting for myself.
items.rationale: Pain at friends' success could relate to Achievement Orientation (competitive comparison), but the emotional quality of longing maps to Envy.

items.text: I feel most authentic when I'm expressing deep emotions, even if it makes others uncomfortable.
items.rationale: Valuing emotional authenticity could map to Emotional Sensitivity, but the emphasis on depth and uniqueness of expression is more characteristic of Envy.

items.text: I want to experience everything life has to offer before it's too late.
items.rationale: Core gluttony drive: insatiable desire for more experiences and stimulation.

items.text: I often overcommit to plans, activities, and adventures because I hate missing out.
items.rationale: FOMO and overextension are hallmarks of the Seven/Gluttony pattern.

items.text: When I'm at a buffet, I want to try a little of everything rather than fill up on one thing.
items.rationale: Literal and metaphorical desire for variety over depth is central to Gluttony.

items.text: People describe me as someone who is always planning the next exciting thing.
items.rationale: Future-oriented excitement-seeking is a core behavioral marker of Gluttony.

items.text: I reframe negative experiences quickly so I can stay in a positive headspace.
items.rationale: Reframing pain into positivity is the classic defense mechanism of the Seven pattern.

items.text: Boredom is one of the most uncomfortable feelings I can experience.
items.rationale: Intolerance of boredom and need for stimulation are central to Gluttony.

items.text: I tend to start many projects but struggle to finish them because something new catches my eye.
items.rationale: Scattered attention driven by novelty-seeking is a key Gluttony behavior.

items.text: I keep my schedule packed because having free, unstructured time makes me anxious.
items.rationale: Filling time to avoid inner emptiness or pain is a Gluttony defense.

items.text: My friends say I'm the life of the party and always up for anything.
items.rationale: Social exuberance and enthusiasm for experience are Gluttony markers.

items.text: I have a hard time sitting with painful emotions—I'd rather distract myself with something fun.
items.rationale: Avoidance of pain through pleasurable distraction is the core Gluttony mechanism.

items.text: I often feel like there's so much to do and see that one lifetime isn't enough.
items.rationale: Sense of limitless appetite for experience is quintessential Gluttony.

items.text: Limiting myself to just one career path or hobby feels suffocating.
items.rationale: Resistance to limitation and desire for multiple options is core Gluttony.

items.text: I sometimes use humor to deflect when conversations get too heavy or emotional.
items.rationale: Humor as deflection from pain is common in Gluttony but could also reflect social anxiety or general coping.

items.text: I love brainstorming and generating ideas more than executing them.
items.rationale: Preference for ideation over execution maps to Gluttony but could also reflect Intellectual Curiosity.

items.text: I get energized by exploring new ideas and concepts across many different fields.
items.rationale: Broad intellectual exploration could map to Intellectual Curiosity (Five) rather than experiential Gluttony (Seven).

items.text: I feel most fulfilled when I know I've made a real difference in someone's life.
items.rationale: Deriving fulfillment from helping others is the core motivation of the Two/Helpfulness pattern.

items.text: I instinctively sense what other people need, often before they say anything.
items.rationale: Empathic attunement to others' needs is a hallmark Two trait.

items.text: I find it very difficult to say no when someone asks me for help.
items.rationale: Inability to refuse requests reflects the compulsive giving pattern of Helpfulness.

items.text: I often put other people's needs ahead of my own, even when it costs me.
items.rationale: Self-sacrifice for others is a defining behavior of the Helpfulness pattern.

items.text: People often come to me with their problems because they know I'll drop everything to listen.
items.rationale: Being the go-to person for emotional support reflects the Two's relational identity.

items.text: I sometimes feel resentful when my efforts to help go unacknowledged.
items.rationale: Hidden resentment from unreciprocated giving is a key shadow aspect of Helpfulness.

items.text: I express love primarily through acts of service and taking care of people.
items.rationale: Love expressed through caretaking is the Two's primary relational strategy.

items.text: I have a hard time identifying what I actually need because I'm so focused on others.
items.rationale: Loss of self-awareness regarding own needs is a core Two pattern.

items.text: I tend to become indispensable to the people I care about.
items.rationale: Making oneself essential to others is a key relational strategy of Helpfulness.

items.text: When I see someone struggling, I feel a physical pull to step in and help.
items.rationale: Compulsive, almost somatic urge to help is characteristic of the Two pattern.

items.text: I adjust my personality depending on who I'm with so I can better connect with them.
items.rationale: Shape-shifting to meet others' emotional needs is a Two relational strategy.

items.text: I secretly keep track of how much I give versus how much I receive in relationships.
items.rationale: Covert scorekeeping reflects the Two's hidden expectation of reciprocity.

items.text: I feel a warm glow when someone tells me they couldn't have done it without me.
items.rationale: Pleasure from being needed maps to Helpfulness but overlaps with Need for Appreciation.

items.text: I'm very good at reading the emotional temperature of a room.
items.rationale: Emotional attunement is strong in Twos but also present in other interpersonally sensitive types.

items.text: I work hard to be seen as someone who is generous and caring by the people around me.
items.rationale: Desire to be seen as caring could reflect Need for Appreciation (Three) image management as much as genuine Helpfulness.

items.text: I feel fundamentally different from other people, and I've felt that way for as long as I can remember.
items.rationale: Sense of being fundamentally different is the core identity of the Four/Individualism pattern.

items.text: I'm drawn to melancholy and find beauty in sadness that others seem to avoid.
items.rationale: Aesthetic appreciation of melancholy is a hallmark Four trait.

items.text: Authenticity matters more to me than almost anything else in life.
items.rationale: The quest for authenticity is the central motivational drive of Individualism.

items.text: I often feel like something essential is missing from my life, though I can't always name what it is.
items.rationale: Chronic sense of longing and incompleteness is the core emotional pattern of the Four.

items.text: I have a rich inner emotional life that most people never see.
items.rationale: Deep, hidden emotional interiority is characteristic of the Four pattern.

items.text: I'm repelled by anything that feels generic, mainstream, or inauthentic.
items.rationale: Rejection of the ordinary in favor of the unique is a defining Four behavior.

items.text: I tend to idealize what I don't have and devalue what I do have.
items.rationale: The push-pull of idealization and devaluation is a core Four psychological mechanism.

items.text: My emotions are intense and can shift dramatically throughout the day.
items.rationale: Emotional intensity and volatility are hallmark Four characteristics.

items.text: I use creative expression—art, music, writing—to process and communicate my deepest feelings.
items.rationale: Creative self-expression as emotional processing is a core Four behavior.

items.text: I sometimes withdraw from people because I feel they can't truly understand me.
items.rationale: Withdrawal due to feeling misunderstood is a classic Four relational pattern.

items.text: I envy people who seem to belong effortlessly while I always feel like an outsider.
items.rationale: Envy and sense of being an outsider are the passion and core wound of the Four.

items.text: I'd rather feel deep pain than feel nothing at all.
items.rationale: Preference for intense emotion over numbness is a defining Four orientation.

items.text: I spend a lot of time reflecting on my identity and who I really am.
items.rationale: Identity preoccupation is central to Fours but also present in introspective types generally.

items.text: I need a lot of alone time to process my feelings and recharge.
items.rationale: Need for solitude maps to Individualism but also to Observation (Five) withdrawal.

items.text: I often retreat into my inner world to analyze and understand my experiences rather than engage with people.
items.rationale: Retreat into inner world could reflect Observation (Five) detachment as much as Four emotional processing.

items.text: I have an insatiable desire to understand how things work at a deep level.
items.rationale: Deep drive to understand systems and mechanisms is the core Five motivation.

items.text: I'd rather spend an evening reading about a complex topic than going to a social event.
items.rationale: Preference for intellectual engagement over social activity is a hallmark Five behavior.

items.text: I collect knowledge the way other people collect possessions—it makes me feel secure.
items.rationale: Knowledge as a source of security is the core Five relationship to information.

items.text: I need to fully understand something before I feel comfortable acting on it.
items.rationale: Need for comprehensive understanding before action is a defining Five pattern.

items.text: I can spend hours going down a rabbit hole researching a topic that fascinates me.
items.rationale: Deep, sustained intellectual immersion is characteristic of the Five pattern.

items.text: I feel drained when people make too many emotional demands on me.
items.rationale: Feeling depleted by emotional demands reflects the Five's scarcity orientation toward energy.

items.text: I prefer to be an expert in a few areas rather than a generalist in many.
items.rationale: Depth over breadth in knowledge acquisition is a Five preference, contrasting with Seven's breadth.

items.text: I often think through problems so thoroughly in my head that I don't feel the need to discuss them with others.
items.rationale: Internal processing and self-sufficiency in problem-solving are core Five behaviors.

items.text: I compartmentalize my life—work, relationships, hobbies—and prefer to keep them separate.
items.rationale: Compartmentalization is a classic Five defense mechanism for managing limited energy.

items.text: I find small talk exhausting and pointless; I'd rather have a deep, substantive conversation.
items.rationale: Preference for depth over superficiality in conversation is a strong Five marker.

items.text: I tend to detach from my emotions and analyze situations from a rational perspective.
items.rationale: Emotional detachment in favor of rational analysis is the Five's primary coping strategy.

items.text: I guard my time and personal space fiercely because they feel like limited resources.
items.rationale: Avarice with time and energy is the passion of the Five type.

items.text: I sometimes feel more comfortable observing life than participating in it.
items.rationale: Observer stance is core to Five but overlaps significantly with the Observation factor.

items.text: I minimize my needs so I won't be dependent on anyone else.
items.rationale: Need minimization is a Five strategy but could also reflect general avoidant tendencies.

items.text: I watch people carefully from the sidelines, noticing patterns and details others miss.
items.rationale: Careful observation from the periphery maps strongly to both Intellectual Curiosity (Five) and Observation.

items.text: I need to know that the people and institutions I rely on are trustworthy before I can relax.
items.rationale: Need for verified trustworthiness before relaxing vigilance is the core Six/Loyalty pattern.

items.text: I tend to imagine worst-case scenarios so I can be prepared for them.
items.rationale: Worst-case thinking as a preparedness strategy is a hallmark Six behavior.

items.text: I'm fiercely loyal to my inner circle, and I expect the same loyalty in return.
items.rationale: Reciprocal loyalty as a core value is the defining trait of the Six pattern.

items.text: I question authority figures to test whether they're truly competent and trustworthy.
items.rationale: Testing authority through questioning is a classic Six behavior pattern.

items.text: I often second-guess my own decisions, going back and forth before committing.
items.rationale: Chronic doubt and indecisiveness are core Six cognitive patterns.

items.text: When things are going well, I find myself waiting for the other shoe to drop.
items.rationale: Anticipatory anxiety during good times is a defining Six experience.

items.text: I feel most secure when I'm part of a group or community that shares my values.
items.rationale: Seeking security through group belonging is a core Six strategy.

items.text: I have a strong sense of duty and responsibility toward the people who depend on me.
items.rationale: Duty and responsibility as motivators are central to the Six pattern.

items.text: I'm always scanning for potential threats or problems that others might overlook.
items.rationale: Hypervigilance and threat-scanning are core Six cognitive habits.

items.text: I struggle to trust my own inner guidance and often seek reassurance from others.
items.rationale: Lack of self-trust and reassurance-seeking are defining Six vulnerabilities.

items.text: Betrayal is the one thing I find almost impossible to forgive.
items.rationale: Extreme sensitivity to betrayal reflects the Six's core fear around trust.

items.text: I sometimes project my own fears onto situations, seeing danger where there may be none.
items.rationale: Projection of fear is the classic defense mechanism of the Six type.

items.text: I like to have a backup plan for my backup plan.
items.rationale: Excessive contingency planning is very Six but could also reflect general anxiety or Perfectionism.

items.text: I'm very attuned to inconsistencies in what people say versus what they do.
items.rationale: Detecting inconsistencies is a Six vigilance behavior but could also reflect Observation.

items.text: I sometimes challenge people aggressively to see if they'll stand their ground or back down.
items.rationale: Counterphobic testing through confrontation could map to Lust (Eight) as much as Six testing behavior.

items.text: I feel most alive when I'm pushing against limits and testing my own strength.
items.rationale: Vitality through intensity and boundary-pushing is the core Eight/Lust pattern.

items.text: I have a natural commanding presence, and people tend to follow my lead without being asked.
items.rationale: Natural authority and dominance are hallmark Eight traits.

items.text: I'd rather have a direct, even confrontational conversation than dance around the truth.
items.rationale: Preference for directness and confrontation over diplomacy is a core Eight behavior.

items.text: I see vulnerability as weakness, and I rarely let people see mine.
items.rationale: Denial of vulnerability and equation with weakness is the Eight's core defense.

items.text: When I sense injustice, I feel a powerful urge to step in and protect the underdog.
items.rationale: Protective instinct toward the vulnerable is a defining Eight motivation.

items.text: I tend to take up a lot of space—physically, emotionally, and conversationally.
items.rationale: Expansive presence and intensity are characteristic Eight behaviors.

items.text: I have an all-or-nothing approach to life—I don't do anything halfway.
items.rationale: Excess and intensity in all pursuits is the passion of Lust in the Enneagram.

items.text: I trust my gut instincts completely and act on them without hesitation.
items.rationale: Gut-level decisiveness and immediate action are core Eight patterns.

items.text: Control is important to me—I never want to be in a position where someone else has power over me.
items.rationale: Need for control and fear of being controlled is the Eight's core fear.

items.text: I respect people who stand up to me more than people who back down.
items.rationale: Respect for strength and directness in others is a classic Eight value.

items.text: When I'm angry, everyone in the room knows it—I don't hide my feelings.
items.rationale: Open, unfiltered expression of anger is a defining Eight behavior.

items.text: I indulge in physical pleasures—food, drink, adventure—with gusto and without guilt.
items.rationale: Unapologetic sensory indulgence reflects the Eight's lust for life and intensity.

items.text: People have told me I can be intimidating, even when I don't intend to be.
items.rationale: Unintentional intimidation is very Eight but could reflect general assertiveness.

items.text: I have strong opinions and I'm not afraid to voice them, even if they're unpopular.
items.rationale: Outspokenness is characteristic of Eights but could also reflect general confidence or Individualism.

items.text: I throw myself into experiences with full intensity and want to feel everything as deeply as possible.
items.rationale: Intensity of experience could map to Gluttony (Seven's desire for more) or Individualism (Four's emotional depth) as well as Lust.

items.text: I work extremely hard to be successful because I need others to see my value.
items.rationale: Achievement driven by need for external validation is the core Three/Need for Appreciation pattern.

items.text: I naturally adapt my image to match what I think will impress the people around me.
items.rationale: Image management and chameleon-like adaptation for approval is a hallmark Three behavior.

items.text: I measure my self-worth largely by my accomplishments and how others perceive my success.
items.rationale: Tying self-worth to achievement and external perception is the core Three wound.

items.text: I feel deeply uncomfortable with failure—it feels like it defines who I am.
items.rationale: Identification with success and devastation at failure is a defining Three pattern.

items.text: I'm highly efficient and goal-oriented; I always know what I need to do to get ahead.
items.rationale: Efficiency and strategic goal pursuit are core Three behavioral markers.

items.text: I sometimes lose touch with my own feelings because I'm so focused on achieving.
items.rationale: Emotional disconnection due to achievement focus is a key Three vulnerability.

items.text: I'm very aware of how I'm perceived and I carefully manage the impression I make.
items.rationale: Impression management is the Three's primary social strategy.

items.text: Receiving praise and recognition energizes me more than almost anything else.
items.rationale: Being energized by recognition reflects the Three's core motivational fuel.

items.text: I can't stand being seen as mediocre or average—I need to stand out.
items.rationale: Need to be exceptional and avoid mediocrity is a core Three drive.

items.text: I've been told I'm a workaholic, but I see it as just being driven.
items.rationale: Reframing workaholism as drive reflects the Three's identification with productivity.

items.text: I sometimes realize I've been performing a role so long that I'm not sure who I really am underneath.
items.rationale: Loss of authentic self beneath performed roles is the Three's deepest existential crisis.

items.text: I compare myself to others constantly and feel anxious when someone seems more successful than me.
items.rationale: Competitive comparison and status anxiety are core Three patterns.

items.text: I'm good at reading what a group values and positioning myself as someone who embodies those values.
items.rationale: Social reading and positioning is very Three but could also reflect Helpfulness (Two) attunement.

items.text: I set very high standards for myself and feel disappointed when I fall short.
items.rationale: High standards could reflect Need for Appreciation or Perfectionism (One).

items.text: I want to be the best at what I do, not just for success but because doing things right matters to me.
items.rationale: Desire to be the best could reflect Three achievement motivation or One Perfectionism depending on whether the driver is image or principle.

items.text: I notice small details in my environment that most people completely overlook.
items.rationale: Heightened perceptual awareness and detail-noticing is a core Observation trait.

items.text: I prefer to watch and understand a situation fully before getting involved.
items.rationale: Observing before participating is the defining behavioral stance of the Observation pattern.

items.text: I'm naturally perceptive about people's motivations and can see through pretense easily.
items.rationale: Perceptiveness about hidden motivations reflects the observer's analytical clarity.

items.text: I often feel like I'm watching my own life from a slight distance, as if I'm a spectator.
items.rationale: Spectator stance toward one's own life is a hallmark of the Observation pattern.

items.text: I take in a lot of information from my surroundings but share very little about myself.
items.rationale: Asymmetric information flow—absorbing much, revealing little—is core to Observation.

items.text: I can sit quietly in a group for a long time, content to listen and observe without contributing.
items.rationale: Comfortable silence and passive observation in groups is a defining Observation behavior.

items.text: I have an excellent memory for things I've observed, even small or seemingly insignificant details.
items.rationale: Detailed observational memory reflects the heightened perceptual processing of this pattern.

items.text: I process experiences internally long after they happen, replaying and analyzing them in my mind.
items.rationale: Delayed internal processing of experiences is characteristic of the observer stance.

items.text: I'm more comfortable being a fly on the wall than being the center of attention.
items.rationale: Preference for peripheral, unnoticed position is a core Observation trait.

items.text: People sometimes find me hard to read because I don't express my reactions outwardly.
items.rationale: Muted external expression despite rich internal processing is characteristic of Observation.

items.text: I can detect subtle shifts in someone's mood or body language that others miss entirely.
items.rationale: Sensitivity to nonverbal cues reflects the heightened perceptual acuity of Observation.

items.text: I maintain a certain emotional distance from situations so I can see them more clearly.
items.rationale: Deliberate emotional distance for clarity is a core Observation strategy.

items.text: I find that I understand things better when I step back and reflect rather than engage directly.
items.rationale: Reflective understanding is Observation-aligned but could also reflect Intellectual Curiosity's analytical approach.

items.text: I'm very private and selective about what I share with others.
items.rationale: Privacy and selectivity in self-disclosure map to Observation but also to Intellectual Curiosity (Five) boundary-setting.

items.text: I spend so much time analyzing and understanding things that I sometimes forget to actually experience them.
items.rationale: Over-analysis at the expense of experience could map to Intellectual Curiosity (Five) as much as Observation.

items.text: I crave harmony and will go to great lengths to avoid conflict in my relationships.
items.rationale: Conflict avoidance and harmony-seeking are the core Nine/Peacefulness patterns.

items.text: I often go along with what others want because it's easier than asserting my own preferences.
items.rationale: Merging with others' agendas and suppressing own preferences is a hallmark Nine behavior.

items.text: I have a calming presence that people are naturally drawn to when they're stressed.
items.rationale: Natural calming effect on others is a characteristic Nine quality.

items.text: I sometimes numb out or zone out when things get too intense or overwhelming.
items.rationale: Narcotization—numbing or zoning out—is the Nine's primary defense mechanism.

items.text: I struggle to know what I really want because I've spent so long accommodating others.
items.rationale: Loss of contact with own desires through chronic accommodation is a core Nine wound.

items.text: I can see every side of an argument, which makes it hard for me to take a firm position.
items.rationale: Seeing all perspectives and difficulty taking a stance is a defining Nine cognitive pattern.

items.text: I tend to procrastinate on things that matter to me while staying busy with less important tasks.
items.rationale: Self-forgetting through displacement activity is a classic Nine avoidance pattern.

items.text: People sometimes mistake my easygoing nature for not caring, but I care deeply—I just don't show it forcefully.
items.rationale: Hidden depth beneath a placid exterior is characteristic of the Nine pattern.

items.text: I feel most at peace when my environment is calm, predictable, and free of tension.
items.rationale: Need for environmental calm and predictability is a core Nine preference.

items.text: I minimize my own problems and tell myself things aren't that bad, even when they are.
items.rationale: Minimization of own distress is a key Nine defense mechanism.

items.text: When there's a disagreement in a group, I automatically try to mediate and find common ground.
items.rationale: Instinctive mediation and bridge-building is a defining Nine social behavior.

items.text: I have a hard time saying no, and I often end up overextended because of it.
items.rationale: Difficulty refusing requests to maintain harmony is a core Nine pattern.

items.text: I find comfort in routines and familiar patterns—change can feel very disruptive to me.
items.rationale: Comfort in routine is Nine-aligned but could also reflect Loyalty (Six) security-seeking.

items.text: I tend to merge with the people closest to me, sometimes losing track of where they end and I begin.
items.rationale: Merging is very Nine but could also reflect Helpfulness (Two) boundary issues.

items.text: I focus so much on keeping everyone happy that I neglect my own needs and eventually feel resentful.
items.rationale: Self-neglect for others' happiness could map to Helpfulness (Two) as much as Peacefulness (Nine).

items.text: I have a strong inner critic that constantly evaluates whether I'm doing things the right way.
items.rationale: The harsh inner critic is the defining psychological feature of the One/Perfectionism pattern.

items.text: I notice errors and flaws immediately—in my own work and in the world around me.
items.rationale: Automatic flaw detection is a core One perceptual habit.

items.text: I believe there is a right way to do things, and I feel compelled to follow it.
items.rationale: Belief in objective correctness and compulsion to adhere to it is the One's core orientation.

items.text: I hold myself to extremely high moral and ethical standards.
items.rationale: Rigid moral standards are a defining One characteristic.

items.text: I feel a deep sense of responsibility to improve things—myself, my work, the world.
items.rationale: Compulsive drive toward improvement is the One's core motivation.

items.text: I get frustrated when people cut corners or don't take their responsibilities seriously.
items.rationale: Frustration with others' lack of standards is a classic One reaction.

items.text: I suppress my anger because I believe a good person shouldn't lose their temper.
items.rationale: Anger suppression due to moral self-image is the One's relationship with their core emotion.

items.text: I often redo tasks that others have completed because they weren't done to my standards.
items.rationale: Redoing others' work to meet personal standards is a behavioral hallmark of Perfectionism.

items.text: I struggle to relax because there's always something that could be done better.
items.rationale: Inability to relax due to perpetual improvement drive is a core One experience.

items.text: I'm my own harshest critic—no one judges me more severely than I judge myself.
items.rationale: Extreme self-criticism is the One's most recognizable internal experience.

items.text: I feel resentful when I follow the rules and others don't, yet they seem to get away with it.
items.rationale: Resentment at perceived unfairness when others don't follow rules is a classic One pattern.

items.text: I have a clear sense of right and wrong, and I feel compelled to speak up when I see injustice.
items.rationale: Moral clarity and compulsion to address injustice is a core One drive.

items.text: I spend more time than most people making sure every detail is correct before submitting my work.
items.rationale: Meticulous attention to detail is very One but could reflect general conscientiousness.

items.text: I feel a simmering frustration that I try to keep under control because expressing it feels wrong.
items.rationale: Controlled frustration is characteristic of Ones but could reflect general emotional regulation.

items.text: I channel my anger into working harder to fix what's broken in the world.
items.rationale: Channeling anger into action could reflect Lust (Eight) justice-seeking as much as One's principled reform.

items.text: When I commit to something, I see it through no matter how difficult it becomes.
items.rationale: Directly captures the core of perseverance: sustained effort despite difficulty.

items.text: I have a strong inner drive to keep going even when others would have given up.
items.rationale: Endurance beyond typical limits is a hallmark of perseverance.

items.text: People describe me as someone who never quits.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of tenacity, a core perseverance trait.

items.text: I believe that hard work and persistence will eventually pay off, even if results are slow.
items.rationale: Belief in delayed gratification through sustained effort maps directly to perseverance.

items.text: I tend to push through physical and emotional exhaustion to finish what I started.
items.rationale: Willingness to endure discomfort for completion is central to perseverance.

items.text: Setbacks motivate me rather than discourage me.
items.rationale: Resilience in the face of obstacles is a defining feature of perseverance.

items.text: I rarely abandon a project once I've invested significant effort into it.
items.rationale: Commitment to completion despite sunk costs reflects perseverance.

items.text: I feel restless and dissatisfied if I leave something unfinished.
items.rationale: Internal discomfort with incompletion drives perseverant behavior.

items.text: Even when a task feels impossible, I find a way to keep making progress.
items.rationale: Finding ways forward under extreme difficulty is core perseverance.

items.text: I've been told I can be stubborn, but I see it as determination.
items.rationale: Self-awareness of how perseverance can be perceived as stubbornness.

items.text: I take pride in my ability to endure hardship longer than most people.
items.rationale: Self-concept built around endurance capacity maps to perseverance.

items.text: When I face repeated failures, I adjust my approach but never my commitment.
items.rationale: Adaptive persistence—changing strategy while maintaining resolve—is sophisticated perseverance.

items.text: I sometimes wonder if my refusal to give up costs me more than it benefits me.
items.rationale: Reflects perseverance but introduces self-doubt about its value, adding ambiguity.

items.text: I keep detailed to-do lists so I can systematically work through every obstacle.
items.rationale: Systematic obstacle management reflects perseverance but the list-keeping behavior overlaps with Planning.

items.text: I create long-term strategies to make sure I can sustain my effort over months or years.
items.rationale: Long-term strategic effort could map to Planning (future orientation and structure) as much as Perseverance.

items.text: I always have a detailed plan before I begin any significant undertaking.
items.rationale: Advance detailed planning before action is the essence of the Planning factor.

items.text: I feel anxious when I don't have a clear roadmap for what's ahead.
items.rationale: Anxiety in the absence of structure reflects a strong need for planning.

items.text: I spend a lot of time thinking about potential outcomes and preparing for each one.
items.rationale: Scenario-based preparation is a core planning behavior.

items.text: My calendar is meticulously organized weeks or months in advance.
items.rationale: Behavioral indicator of extensive forward planning.

items.text: I prefer to anticipate problems rather than deal with them as they arise.
items.rationale: Proactive problem anticipation is a hallmark of the planning orientation.

items.text: People come to me when they need someone to organize a complex project.
items.rationale: Third-person recognition of organizational and planning ability.

items.text: I make contingency plans for my contingency plans.
items.rationale: Layered backup planning reflects an extreme planning orientation.

items.text: Spontaneity makes me uncomfortable; I'd rather know what to expect.
items.rationale: Discomfort with unplanned situations directly reflects the planning factor.

items.text: Before making a decision, I research every available option thoroughly.
items.rationale: Exhaustive information gathering before decisions is a planning behavior.

items.text: I break large goals into small, manageable steps with clear timelines.
items.rationale: Goal decomposition with timelines is a textbook planning strategy.

items.text: I find it hard to relax unless I know everything is accounted for and scheduled.
items.rationale: Inability to relax without complete scheduling reflects strong planning needs.

items.text: I mentally rehearse important conversations and events before they happen.
items.rationale: Mental rehearsal is a cognitive planning strategy applied to social situations.

items.text: I sometimes over-prepare because I worry about what could go wrong.
items.rationale: Over-preparation maps to planning but the worry component introduces possible overlap with Skepticism or Suspicion.

items.text: I need to feel certain about a situation before I can move forward with confidence.
items.rationale: Need for certainty relates to planning but could also reflect Skepticism's doubt orientation.

items.text: I question whether my plans will actually work out, so I keep revising them obsessively.
items.rationale: Obsessive revision driven by doubt could map to Skepticism (questioning reliability of outcomes) as much as Planning.

items.text: I naturally sense what others need and take satisfaction in being indispensable to them.
items.rationale: Deriving identity from being needed is central to the Pride factor in the Enneagram (Type 2 dynamic).

items.text: I feel a deep sense of worth when people depend on me for emotional support.
items.rationale: Self-worth tied to being depended upon is a core Pride manifestation.

items.text: I sometimes believe I understand other people's feelings better than they do themselves.
items.rationale: Inflated sense of emotional insight reflects the grandiosity embedded in Pride.

items.text: It's hard for me to admit that I need help because I see myself as the helper.
items.rationale: Difficulty receiving help due to helper identity is a classic Pride pattern.

items.text: I give generously to others, but I'd feel humiliated if I had to ask for the same in return.
items.rationale: Asymmetric giving/receiving with shame about neediness is a hallmark of Pride.

items.text: I subtly adjust my personality to become exactly what each person in my life needs.
items.rationale: Shape-shifting to meet others' needs reflects Pride's interpersonal strategy.

items.text: When someone I've helped doesn't acknowledge my contribution, I feel deeply hurt.
items.rationale: Expectation of recognition for help given is a core Pride vulnerability.

items.text: I have a special ability to make people feel seen and cared for.
items.rationale: Self-concept as uniquely empathic and caring reflects Pride's inflated self-image.

items.text: I often put others' needs before my own, sometimes without even realizing it.
items.rationale: Automatic self-sacrifice reflects the Pride pattern of denying personal needs.

items.text: People would describe me as warm and giving, but they might not realize how much I expect in return emotionally.
items.rationale: Hidden emotional expectations beneath a generous exterior is a sophisticated Pride indicator.

items.text: I feel secretly superior to people who are less emotionally attuned than I am.
items.rationale: Covert superiority based on emotional intelligence is a direct Pride expression.

items.text: I can become possessive of the people I care about because I've invested so much in them.
items.rationale: Possessiveness rooted in investment reflects Pride's relational entitlement.

items.text: I sometimes wonder if people only value me for what I do for them, not for who I am.
items.rationale: This reflects Pride's vulnerability but could also indicate a more general insecurity.

items.text: I work hard to present the best version of myself so that others will admire and appreciate me.
items.rationale: Image management for admiration maps to Pride but overlaps with Vanity's concern with self-presentation.

items.text: I carefully craft my image so that others see me as successful, attractive, and put-together.
items.rationale: Image crafting for external validation could map to Vanity (Type 3 image focus) as much as Pride.

items.text: I carry a simmering frustration about things that aren't done the right way.
items.rationale: Chronic frustration about standards not being met is central to Resentment (Type 1 anger).

items.text: I often feel angry about injustices, even small ones, but I try to keep it under control.
items.rationale: Suppressed anger about perceived injustice is a hallmark of Resentment.

items.text: It bothers me deeply when people don't follow the rules or take shortcuts.
items.rationale: Moral indignation about rule-breaking reflects the Resentment pattern.

items.text: I hold myself to very high standards, and I resent it when others don't do the same.
items.rationale: Resentment arising from asymmetric standards is a core expression of this factor.

items.text: I notice every flaw and imperfection, and it creates a constant low-level irritation in me.
items.rationale: Pervasive irritation driven by perfectionism is a defining Resentment characteristic.

items.text: I feel like I'm always the one doing things correctly while others get away with being careless.
items.rationale: Perceived unfairness in effort and correctness fuels Resentment.

items.text: When I see someone behaving irresponsibly, I feel a surge of righteous anger.
items.rationale: Righteous anger at irresponsibility is a classic Resentment trigger.

items.text: I have a strong inner critic that judges both myself and others harshly.
items.rationale: A punitive inner critic directed inward and outward is central to Resentment.

items.text: I often replay situations where I felt wronged, and the anger doesn't fade easily.
items.rationale: Rumination on perceived wrongs with persistent anger defines Resentment.

items.text: I try to be patient, but inside I'm seething when things aren't fair.
items.rationale: Suppressed seething beneath a patient exterior is a classic Resentment dynamic.

items.text: People might see me as rigid, but I just believe there's a right way to do things.
items.rationale: Self-justified rigidity based on moral correctness reflects Resentment.

items.text: I feel bitter when my efforts to do the right thing go unrecognized or unrewarded.
items.rationale: Bitterness about unrecognized moral effort is a direct Resentment expression.

items.text: I sometimes catch myself being critical of others and wish I could be more accepting.
items.rationale: Self-awareness of critical tendencies maps to Resentment but the desire for acceptance introduces some ambiguity.

items.text: I get frustrated when I can't live up to my own impossibly high expectations.
items.rationale: Self-directed frustration about standards maps to Resentment but could also reflect Perseverance-related self-demand.

items.text: I push myself relentlessly because anything less than excellence feels like a moral failure.
items.rationale: Relentless self-pushing with moral framing could map to Perseverance (endurance) as much as Resentment (inner critic).

items.text: I question everything before I accept it, even things most people take for granted.
items.rationale: Habitual questioning of accepted truths is the core of Skepticism.

items.text: I tend to play devil's advocate because I genuinely see the flaws in most arguments.
items.rationale: Contrarian thinking driven by flaw detection is a hallmark of Skepticism.

items.text: I have trouble committing to decisions because I can always see reasons why each option might fail.
items.rationale: Decision paralysis from seeing potential failures reflects Skepticism's doubt orientation.

items.text: My mind automatically generates worst-case scenarios for any plan or proposal.
items.rationale: Automatic worst-case thinking is a cognitive signature of Skepticism.

items.text: I'm wary of people who seem overly confident or certain about things.
items.rationale: Distrust of certainty in others reflects the Skepticism factor.

items.text: I often second-guess myself even after I've made a well-reasoned decision.
items.rationale: Chronic second-guessing despite rational analysis is a core Skepticism behavior.

items.text: I need to test ideas thoroughly before I can trust them.
items.rationale: Requiring empirical testing before trust reflects Skepticism's evidence-based doubt.

items.text: People sometimes find me exhausting because I challenge every assumption.
items.rationale: Third-person observation of relentless assumption-challenging maps to Skepticism.

items.text: I find it very difficult to take things at face value.
items.rationale: Inability to accept surface-level information is a defining Skepticism trait.

items.text: I oscillate between courage and doubt, often within the same hour.
items.rationale: Rapid oscillation between confidence and doubt is characteristic of Skepticism (Type 6 ambivalence).

items.text: I'm drawn to authority figures but simultaneously want to challenge them.
items.rationale: Ambivalent relationship with authority is a classic Skepticism pattern.

items.text: I prepare for the worst because I've learned that optimism can be dangerous.
items.rationale: Defensive pessimism rooted in distrust of positive outcomes reflects Skepticism.

items.text: I sometimes wonder if my constant questioning prevents me from ever feeling at peace.
items.rationale: Self-reflective awareness of questioning's cost maps to Skepticism but introduces existential ambiguity.

items.text: I analyze people's motives carefully before deciding whether to trust them.
items.rationale: Motive analysis before trust maps to Skepticism but overlaps with Suspicion's interpersonal vigilance.

items.text: I watch people closely because I believe most of them have hidden agendas.
items.rationale: Belief in hidden agendas with interpersonal surveillance could map to Suspicion as much as Skepticism.

items.text: I'm always scanning my environment for potential threats or dangers.
items.rationale: Hypervigilant environmental scanning for threats is central to Suspicion.

items.text: I find it very hard to trust people until they've proven themselves over a long period of time.
items.rationale: Extended trust-building requirements reflect the core of Suspicion.

items.text: When someone is unusually nice to me, my first thought is to wonder what they want.
items.rationale: Interpreting kindness as manipulation is a hallmark of Suspicion.

items.text: I keep my guard up in most social situations because I've been burned before.
items.rationale: Defensive social posture based on past betrayal reflects Suspicion.

items.text: I notice inconsistencies in what people say and do, and it makes me distrust them.
items.rationale: Tracking behavioral inconsistencies as evidence of untrustworthiness is a Suspicion pattern.

items.text: I often feel like people are talking about me behind my back.
items.rationale: Paranoid ideation about being discussed negatively is a direct Suspicion indicator.

items.text: I test people's loyalty before I let them into my inner circle.
items.rationale: Loyalty testing as a prerequisite for closeness is a classic Suspicion behavior.

items.text: I share very little personal information because it could be used against me.
items.rationale: Information withholding as self-protection reflects Suspicion's defensive orientation.

items.text: I've ended relationships because I suspected the other person wasn't being fully honest with me.
items.rationale: Relationship termination based on suspected dishonesty is a behavioral consequence of Suspicion.

items.text: I read between the lines in every conversation, looking for what's really being communicated.
items.rationale: Searching for hidden meanings in communication reflects Suspicion's interpretive vigilance.

items.text: I feel safest when I know exactly where I stand with everyone around me.
items.rationale: Need for interpersonal clarity as a safety mechanism maps to Suspicion.

items.text: I have a small number of people I truly trust, and even with them I hold something back.
items.rationale: Restricted trust even within close relationships is a defining Suspicion characteristic.

items.text: I sometimes realize my distrust was unfounded, but I still can't shake the feeling.
items.rationale: Awareness that suspicion is irrational yet persistent maps to Suspicion but shows some ego-dystonic quality.

items.text: I spend a lot of mental energy trying to figure out whether people's intentions are genuine.
items.rationale: Cognitive preoccupation with others' intentions maps to Suspicion but could overlap with Skepticism's analytical doubt.

items.text: I doubt whether any system or institution truly has my best interests at heart.
items.rationale: Institutional distrust could map to Skepticism (questioning systems intellectually) as much as Suspicion (feeling personally threatened).

items.text: I'm highly aware of how I come across to others and I adjust my presentation accordingly.
items.rationale: Self-monitoring and image adjustment is the core of Vanity (Type 3 dynamic).

items.text: Success and achievement are central to how I define my self-worth.
items.rationale: Identity fused with achievement and success is a hallmark of Vanity.

items.text: I can read a room quickly and become whatever version of myself will be most impressive.
items.rationale: Chameleon-like self-presentation for impression management is central to Vanity.

items.text: I feel empty or worthless when I'm not accomplishing something visible and impressive.
items.rationale: Emptiness without external achievement reflects Vanity's hollow core.

items.text: I compare myself to others constantly and feel driven to come out on top.
items.rationale: Competitive social comparison is a defining Vanity behavior.

items.text: I've been accused of being superficial, but I think appearances matter more than people admit.
items.rationale: Valuing appearances while defending that value reflects Vanity's worldview.

items.text: I find it difficult to distinguish between who I really am and the image I project.
items.rationale: Identity confusion between authentic self and projected image is a core Vanity struggle.

items.text: I feel a rush of energy and confidence when I know I'm being admired.
items.rationale: Admiration as a source of vitality and confidence is central to Vanity.

items.text: I tend to embellish my accomplishments to make a stronger impression.
items.rationale: Achievement embellishment for impression management is a direct Vanity behavior.

items.text: Failure terrifies me because it threatens the successful image I've built.
items.rationale: Fear of failure rooted in image threat is a core Vanity anxiety.

items.text: I'm very attuned to status markers—titles, brands, associations—and what they communicate about a person.
items.rationale: Attention to status symbols and their social signaling reflects Vanity's value system.

items.text: I can be so focused on achieving goals that I lose touch with my own feelings.
items.rationale: Emotional disconnection through achievement focus is a classic Vanity pattern.

items.text: I sometimes feel like an imposter, as if the person everyone admires isn't really me.
items.rationale: Imposter feelings reflect Vanity's image-self gap but could indicate broader insecurity.

items.text: I want people to see me as someone special who makes a real difference in their lives.
items.rationale: Desire to be seen as special maps to Vanity but the helping element introduces overlap with Pride.

items.text: I go out of my way to help others because I want to be seen as generous and caring.
items.rationale: Helping motivated by image concerns could map to Pride (need to be needed) as much as Vanity (image management).
